Last compiled: 2019-08-09

Workflow Overview

  1. Tag 0s as nondetects
  2. Tag 0<Area<1000 as censored
  3. Filter out known contaminants
  4. Calculate RPA
  5. Split data into samples and method blank
  6. Subtract RPAs of method blank

This will give you sample data with 0s and possibly negative values for RPA and flags for nondetects and peaks that should be censored.

  1. Remove compounds that are not found in more than 2 samples (at least 3 samples) with RPA > 0 8a. Set RPA for nondetects, censored, and all RPA <= 0 to 1/IS 8b. Set RPA for nondetects, censored, and all RPA < 0 to 0 (for venn diagram)
  2. Check for and remove any obvious outliers
  3. Create wide dataframes from 8a and 8b.

Extract sample name from filename, set cultivar

gc_tidy <- 
  gc_tidy %>% 
  mutate(cultivar = "Q",
         plant_num = str_extract(filename, "(?<=Hop_)\\d+(?=_)"), #blanks will be NA
         sample = ifelse(!is.na(plant_num), paste0(cultivar, plant_num), filename)) %>% 
  select(filename, cultivar, plant_num, sample, everything())

gc_tidy <-
  gc_tidy %>%
  mutate(ND = area == 0,
         Censor = area > 0 & area < 1000)

Remove known contaminants and problematic peaks

Contaminants:

  • Propanoic acid, 2-methyl-, 1-(1, 1-dimethylethyl)-2methyl-1, 3-propanediyl ester (from nitrile gloves)
  • Toluene (very large peak, seems unlikely that it is a natural product)

These chlorinated compounds are likely pesticides:

  • Benzaldehyde, 2,6-dichloro-
  • Benzene, chloro-

These compounds should be removed for other reasons:

  • 141: Unknown that shows up in method blanks. Nicole doesnt know what it is, but is pretty sure it is contaminant.
  • Anything with an RT earlier than 3.3-ish (currently corresponds to No.> 91)

Problematic peaks includes peaks that I decided were bad, and should be marked as not found in all files, but was too lazy to go through and mark in Ion Analytics. Its much easier to just exclude them in R.

    1. Heptane, 2,4-dimethyl-: Check all. Bad peak, borderline Q value.
    1. 1 (DCSE): Hitting same peak as (180) Pentane, 1-nitro-. Mark all as not found. Remove from method when done with deconvolution so it doesnt get propogated to the next dataset.
    1. 37: Pretty bad peak. Mark all as not found?
  • (268, 269): unknown 64 = limonene? Mark 64 as not found.
    1. 2-Nonanone: Bad peak. Mark all as not found
    1. Fenchol: Bad peak. Mark all as not found
    1. 158: Matches a few other peaks. Mark all as not found
    1. 127: one ion low. mark all as not found. Consider removing from method (could be decanal + noise?)
    1. Geranylacetone: Hits same peak as (556) 5,9-Undecadien-2-one Mark all as not found.

Calculate RPA

#extract napthalene D8 area
gc_IS <- gc_tidy.1 %>% 
  filter(Compound == "Naphthalene-D8") %>%
  rename(IS = area) %>% 
  select(sample, IS)

#join with gc.tidy and mutate to calculate RPA
gc_tidy.2 <- full_join(gc_tidy.1, gc_IS)
Joining, by = "sample"
gc_tidy.2 <- gc_tidy.2 %>% 
  mutate(RPA = area/IS) %>% 
  #don't need Naphtalene-D8 anymore
  filter(Compound != "Naphthalene-D8")
gc_tidy.2

Method blank subtraction

I have two method blanks, one from the beginning and one from the end. I could average them and subtract from all samples or subtract the start blank from the start samples and the end blank from the end samples.

For now, Im just using the end data, so Ill just use the end blank.

#split into samples and background
gc_blank <-
  gc_tidy.2 %>%
  filter(str_detect(filename,"blank_end"))
gc_tidy.3 <-
  gc_tidy.2 %>% 
  filter(!str_detect(filename, "blank"))

#subtract background
gc_blank.1 <-
  gc_blank %>%
  rename(background = RPA) %>% 
  select(Compound, background)

gc_tidy.3 <- left_join(gc_tidy.3, gc_blank.1)
Joining, by = "Compound"
gc_tidy.4 <-
  gc_tidy.3 %>%
  mutate(RPA = RPA - background)

Deal with non-detects, censored peaks, and other zeros and negative values

Nondetects were zeros to begin with, not found by IonAnalytics at all. Censored peaks are those with peak area < 1000. According to the Robbat lab, areas < 1000 are not accurate due to being below the LOD. There are multiple options for dealing with this, but they usually set those peaks to zero. There may be other RPA values <= 0 due to subtracting the method blank.

I want to deal with these values in two ways:

  1. Set them all to zero. This will be useful for calculating numbers of compounds detected in various samples and for making venn diagrams.

  2. Set them all to 1/IS. This will be useful for log-transforming data since log(0) = -inf.

On second thought, I think all I need is a tidy dataset with zeroes set to 1/IS and a column for present or not

gc_tidy.7 <-
  gc_tidy.6 %>%                             # Set RPA to a very small number...
  mutate(RPA = case_when(ND            ~ 500/IS, # if peaks were always not detected
                         Censor        ~ 500/IS, # or if their original areas were  < 1000
                         RPA < 500/IS  ~ 500/IS, # or if their areas after background subtraction < 500
                         TRUE    ~ RPA),
         present = case_when(ND           ~ FALSE,
                             Censor       ~ FALSE,
                             RPA <= 500/IS ~ FALSE,
                             TRUE         ~ TRUE)) %>%
  select(sample, cultivar, density_start, density_end, mean_percent_damage, twister_damage, No., Compound, RPA, rt, ri, present)

#How many compounds detected in each sample?
gc_tidy.7 %>%
  group_by(sample) %>%
  summarize(num_compounds = sum(present))

Remove rare peaks

Remove compounds that are found in 5 or fewer samples.

gc_tidy.7 %>% count(Compound)
gc_tidy.final <-
  gc_tidy.7 %>% 
  group_by(Compound) %>% #for each compound...
  filter(sum(present) >= 5)
gc_tidy.final %>% ungroup() %>% count(sample) #down to 94 compounds

Create wide data frame

gc_wide <- 
  gc_tidy.final %>%
  ungroup() %>% 
  select(-rt, -ri, -No., -present) %>%
  spread(key = Compound, value = RPA)

Preliminary Data Analysis

Multivariate normality

For some reason (data too large? numbers too small?) the mvn() function often fails due to a singular matrix error. Below, Ive run it on random subsets of the data and log transformation seems to improve normality. Interestingly, scaling seems to make things worse.

gc_tidy.final %>% 
  ggplot(aes(RPA)) + geom_histogram()

gc_tidy.final %>% 
  ggplot(aes(log(RPA))) + geom_histogram()

library(MVN)
sROC 0.1-2 loaded
metavars <- c("sample", "cultivar", "density_start", "density_end", "mean_percent_damage", "twister_damage")
test <-
  gc_tidy.final %>%
  ungroup() %>% 
  select(-rt, -ri, -No., -present) %>% 
  spread(key = Compound, value = RPA) %>% 
  select(-metavars) %>%
  mutate_all(~.*1000) %>%
  mvn(mvnTest = "mardia",
      transform = "log",
      multivariatePlot = "qq",
      scale = TRUE)

test
$multivariateNormality

$univariateNormality

$Descriptives
NA

So this dataset is clearly zero-inflated (or rather, small number introduced by data pre-treatment inflated). I should consider distance-based methods as a sanity-check.
